I"@<p>As part of the UK Government’s <a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-54981425">green revolution</a> there will be a ban on the sale of <a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-54981425">petrol and deisel cars from 2030</a>.  The only cars for sale will be Electric Vehicles ( EV ) but given the Government’s track record in combating <a href="https://www.un.org/en/un75/climate-crisis-race-we-can-win">climate crisis</a> how effective will it be?</p>

<p>There are many instances of governement policy not delivering its aims. Gordon Brown introduced tax breaks for diesel cars as the UK chancellor in 2001 because they emit less CO2 than petrol-powered cars, but it is now known that they emit other <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/oct/01/uk-government-wrong-to-subsidise-diesel-says-former-minister">harmful pollutants</a>. This government policy resulted in 40% of the cars on the road being diesel and an on-going investigation on their <a href="https://erj.ersjournals.com/content/erj/17/4/733.full.pdf">impact on health</a>.</p>

<p>Electric Vehicles have no exhaust pipe therefore it has zero emissions when on the road. But that is only looking at one part of the problem of a complex problem. A much better approach would be to consider the whole life cycle of the car. There are three elements in life cycle analysis: the amount of  <a href="https://climatechangeconnection.org/emissions/co2-equivalents/">CO2 Equivelant</a>( CO<sub>2</sub>e ) that is produced in making the EV, the amount of CO<sub>2</sub>e produced during the operation of the EV and finally its end-of-life, in otherwords its disposal. Searching on the web to find out the data to compare th elife cycle of an EV with petrol and diesel is very difficult because of the many <a href="https://innovationorigins.com/en/producing-gasoline-and-diesel-emits-more-co2-than-we-thought/">assumptions</a> that are used to develop an opinion. However, a study by <a href="https://ricardo.com/news-and-media/news-and-press/ricardo-study-demonstrates-importance-of-whole-lif">Ricardo demonstrates CO2 emissions from a life cycle analysis</a> which shows a different picture that it can give. For a standard gasoline vehicle the estimated lifecycle emissions if 24 tonees CO<sub>2</sub>e , with 5.6 tonnes CO2e estimated in its production. For a EV it is 19 Tonnes CO<sub>2</sub>e  with 8.8 Tonnes CO<sub>2</sub>e  estimated in its production. Therefore based on these estimaes the reduction in CO<sub>2</sub>e over the life of an EV is around 20% which is good but maybe not what the banner headline of “zero emmisions” is potraying.</p>

<p>The government’s plan for a green revolution is based on <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-ten-point-plan-for-a-green-industrial-revolution">ten key points plan for a green revolution</a> which includes the decarbonisation of the running of the economy but doesn’t take into account any life cycle analysis. Another aspect is that it doesn’t take into account the overall transport system. For example carrying out a life cycle analysis impact of HS2 <a href="https://usefulprojects.co.uk/project/high-speed-two/">High Speed Two (HS2)</a> aims to create a world class high speed rail network to support economic growth, both in cities it connects, and for the UK.</p>

