<p>It is estimated that an <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/blog/2012/jul/16/electric-trains-diesel-green-carbon">electric train uses</a> less “Typically an electric train emits 20–35% less carbon per passenger mile than a diesel train.” and each passenger journey is typically <a href="https://www.seat61.com/CO2flights.htm">around 24 Kg CO<sub>2</sub>e </a> HS2 claim that it will caryy <a href="https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/hs2_claim_it_will_carry_over_300">300,000 passnegers per day</a>  <a href="https://iea.org.uk/hs2-wont-help-the-government-meet-its-climate-change-goals/">HS2 life-span of 120 years</a> ( it is interesting that the success of HS2 is based on an assumption of 120 years - look what has happened in the last year from a pandemic! )</p>

<p>There is no information about decomssion a railway line but lets assume that it is left to rot.  Total 315360 Tonnes ( need to check ) - may need to calculate per year .</p>

<p>In 2019, net territorial emissions in the UK of the basket of seven greenhouse gases covered by the Kyoto Protocol were estimated to be 454.8 million tonnes carbon dioxide equivalent (MtCO2e), a decrease of 2.8% compared to the 2018 figure of 468.1 million tonnes and 43.8% lower than they were in 1990 <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/957887/2019_Final_greenhouse_gas_emissions_statistical_release.pdf">report</a> - MtCO2e refers to million tonnes of carbon dioxide equivalent. This is a consistent measure of assessing the contribution of greenhouse gases to global warming.</p>

<p>Not taking ito account he full life cycle of anything that is produced whether it is vehicles, food or anything els that we consume doesn’t take into account th efull picture and therefore the progress that we hope to make against Climate Crisis may not be as effective as we hoped. By not taking into account a wider picture usually results in a failure of the original aims.</p>

<p>Moving to zero emmisions vehicles is a great step forward for not onluy the fight against the climate crisis but also improving health in urban areas with improved air quality. But a clearer analysis needs to be carried out to make sure that governement policies will be as effetive overall as they claim - th edevil is in the detail. One approach is using a life cycle analysis. Lets hope that we don’t end up with the similar situation that we had with diesel vehicles!</p>
